07731nam a22010815i 9783110690347DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106903477 a10.1515/97831106903472doi  a(DE-B1597)542154  a(OCoLC)1226678311  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0170002bisacsh00aMediation and Immediacy :bA Key Issue for the Semiotics of Religion /ced. by Massimo Leone, Jenny Ponzo, Robert A. Yelle. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (X, 302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Reason : Theory in the Study of Religion ,x0080-0848 ;v6200tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tTable of Contents -- tFigures -- tIntroduction: Mediation and immediacy, a key issue for the semiotics of religion -- tPart I: Classical traditions -- tImmediacy and mediation in Philo’s interpretation of divine names -- t“Anì velo mal’akh”: Are angels in the Torah a sort of medium? -- tThe angel as an intercultural medium -- tMedieval theology and the theory of signs -- tTranscending the body: The semiotics of an out-of-body experience reported by Mechthild of Magdeburg -- tThe supremacy of the Qur’anic sign and its impacts on the Arabic Muslim culture -- tArguments for immediacy and mediation in classical Advaita-Vedānta -- tPart II: Contemporary movements -- tReligious-artistic epiphanies in 20th-century literature: Joyce, Claudel, Weil, C.S. Lewis, Rebora, and Papini -- tOn vain repetitions: The enactment of collective subjectivities through speaking in unison -- tThe other Buddha: Leaving monasteries, fighting the enemy -- tPart III: Religious legal systems -- tMediation and immediacy in the Jewish legal tradition -- tThe doodling of Jesus: A semiotic inquiry into the rhetoric of immediacy -- tLegal theology and communication: The meaning of Christian eschatology between immanence and transcendence in contemporary social sciences -- tPost-secular jurisprudence: A visual semiotics of the sacred source of law’s authority -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion, like any other domain of culture, is mediated through symbolic forms and communicative behaviors, which allow the coordination of group conduct in ritual and the representation of the divine or of tradition as an intersubjective reality. While many traditions hold out the promise of immediate access to the divine, or to some transcendent dimension of experience, such promises depend for their realization as well on the possibility of mediation, which is necessarily conducted through channels of communication and exchange, such as prayers or sacrifices. An understanding of such modes of semiosis is therefore necessary even and especially when mediation is denied by a tradition in the name of the 'ineffability" of the deity or of mystical experience. This volume models and promotes an interdisciplinary dialogue and cross-cultural perspective on these issues by asking prominent semioticians, historians of religion and of art, linguists, sociologists of religion, and philosophers of law to reflect from a semiotic perspective on the topic of mediation and immediacy in religious traditions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aKommunikation. 4aMediation. 4aReligion. 4aSemiotik. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aCommunication.  aMediation.  aReligion.  aSemiotics.1 aBernoussi, Mohamed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummins, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeritier, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a